[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:fasthttp-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Several methods have been devised that increase the effectiveness of memory management.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Virtual memory systems separate the memory addresses used by a process from actual physical addresses, allowing separation of processes and increasing the size of the virtual address space beyond the available amount of RAM using paging or swapping to secondary storage.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The quality of the virtual memory manager can have an extensive effect on overall system performance.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The system allows a computer to appear as if it may have more memory available than physically present, thereby allowing multiple processes to share it.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Burroughs/Unisys MCP, and OS/360 and successors, memory is managed by the operating system.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Unix-like operating systems, memory is managed at the application level.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory management within an address space is generally categorized as either manual memory management or automatic memory management.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The task of fulfilling an allocation request consists of locating a block of unused memory of sufficient size.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory requests are satisfied by allocating portions from a large pool of memory called the *heap* or *free store*.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] At any given time, some parts of the heap are in use, while some are "free" (unused) and thus available for future allocations.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In the C language, the function which allocates memory from the heap is called `malloc` and the function which takes previously allocated memory and marks it as "free" (to be used by future allocations) is called `free`.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Several issues complicate the implementation, such as external fragmentation, which arises when there are many small gaps between allocated memory blocks, which invalidates their use for an allocation request.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The allocator's metadata can also inflate the size of (individually) small allocations.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory management system must track outstanding allocations to ensure that they do not overlap and that no memory is ever "lost" (i.e. that there are no "memory leaks").
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The specific dynamic memory allocation algorithm implemented can impact performance significantly.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A study conducted in 1994 by Digital Equipment Corporation illustrates the overheads involved for a variety of allocators.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The lowest average instruction path length required to allocate a single memory slot was 52 (as measured with an instruction level profiler on a variety of software).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Since the precise location of the allocation is not known in advance, the memory is accessed indirectly, usually through a pointer reference.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Fixed-size blocks allocation, also called memory pool allocation, uses a free list of fixed-size blocks of memory (often all of the same size).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This works well for simple embedded systems where no large objects need to be allocated but suffers from fragmentation especially with long memory addresses.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] However, due to the significantly reduced overhead, this method can substantially improve performance for objects that need frequent allocation and deallocation, and so it is often used in video games.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In this system, memory is allocated into several pools of memory instead of just one, where each pool represents blocks of memory of a certain power of two in size, or blocks of some other convenient size progression.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] All blocks of a particular size are kept in a sorted linked list or tree and all new blocks that are formed during allocation are added to their respective memory pools for later use.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] If a smaller size is requested than is available, the smallest available size is selected and split.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When a block is split, it is divided into two smaller blocks, and each smaller block becomes a unique "buddy" to the other.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] One of the resulting parts is selected, and the process repeats until the request is complete.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When a block is allocated, the allocator will start with the smallest sufficiently large block to avoid needlessly breaking blocks.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When a block is freed, it is compared to its buddy.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] If they are both free, they are combined and placed in the correspondingly larger-sized buddy-block list.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This memory allocation mechanism preallocates memory chunks suitable to fit objects of a certain type or size.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] These chunks are called caches and the allocator only has to keep track of a list of free cache slots.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Constructing an object will use any one of the free cache slots and destructing an object will add a slot back to the free cache slot list.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This technique alleviates memory fragmentation and is efficient as there is no need to search for a suitable portion of memory, as any open slot will suffice.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Although there is no need of manually freeing memory allocated this way, as it is automatically freed when the function that called `alloca` returns, there exists a risk of overflow.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] And since alloca is an *ad hoc* expansion seen in many systems but never in POSIX or the C standard, its behavior in case of a stack overflow is undefined.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A safer version of alloca called `_malloca`, which reports errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to malloc when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The proper management of memory in an application is a difficult problem, and several different strategies for handling memory management have been devised.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Special declarations may allow local variables to retain values between invocations of the procedure, or may allow local variables to be accessed by other subroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The automatic allocation of local variables makes recursion possible, to a depth limited by available memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Garbage collection is a strategy for automatically detecting memory allocated to objects that are no longer usable in a program, and returning that allocated memory to a pool of free memory locations.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This method is in contrast to "manual" memory management where a programmer explicitly codes memory requests and memory releases in the program.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] While automatic garbage collection has the advantages of reducing programmer workload and preventing certain kinds of memory allocation bugs, garbage collection does require memory resources of its own, and can compete with the application program for processor time.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Reference counting is a strategy for detecting that memory is no longer usable by a program by maintaining a counter for how many independent pointers point to the memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Whenever a new pointer points to a piece of memory, the programmer is supposed to increase the counter.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When the pointer changes where it points, or when the pointer is no longer pointing to any area or has itself been freed, the counter should decrease.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When the counter drops to zero, the memory should be considered unused and freed.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Some reference counting systems require programmer involvement and some are implemented automatically by the compiler.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A disadvantage of reference counting is that circular references can develop which cause a memory leak to occur.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This can be mitigated by either adding the concept of a "weak reference" (a reference that does not participate in reference counting, but is notified when the area it is pointing to is no longer valid) or by combining reference counting and garbage collection together.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] A memory pool is a technique of automatically deallocating memory based on the state of the application, such as the lifecycle of a request or transaction.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The idea is that many applications execute large chunks of code which may generate memory allocations, but that there is a point in execution where all of those chunks are known to be no longer valid.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] For example, in a web service, after each request the web service no longer needs any of the memory allocated during the execution of the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Therefore, rather than keeping track of whether or not memory is currently being referenced, the memory is allocated according to the request or lifecycle stage with which it is associated.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] When that request or stage has passed, all associated memory is deallocated simultaneously.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Virtual memory is a method of decoupling the memory organization from the physical hardware.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The applications operate on memory via *virtual addresses*.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Each attempt by the application to access a particular virtual memory address results in the virtual memory address being translated to an actual *physical address*.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In this way the addition of virtual memory enables granular control over memory systems and methods of access.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In virtual memory systems the operating system limits how a process can access the memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] This feature, called memory protection, can be used to disallow a process to read or write to memory that is not allocated to it, preventing malicious or malfunctioning code in one program from interfering with the operation of another.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Even though the memory allocated for specific processes is normally isolated, processes sometimes need to be able to share information.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Shared memory is one of the fastest techniques for inter-process communication.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory is usually classified by access rate into primary storage and secondary storage.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory management systems, among other operations, also handle the moving of information between these two levels of memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] An operating system manages various resources in the computing system.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory subsystem is the system element for managing memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory subsystem combines the hardware memory resource and the MCP OS software that manages the resource.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory subsystem manages the physical memory and the virtual memory of the system (both part of the hardware resource).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The virtual memory extends physical memory by using extra space on a peripheral device, usually disk.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for moving code and data between main and virtual memory in a process known as overlaying.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Burroughs was the first commercial implementation of virtual memory (although developed at Manchester University for the Ferranti Atlas computer) and integrated virtual memory with the system design of the B5000 from the start (in 1961) needing no external memory management unit (MMU).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for mapping logical requests for memory blocks to physical portions of memory (segments) which are found in the list of free segments.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Descriptors are essential in providing memory safety and security so that operations cannot overflow or underflow the referenced block (commonly known as buffer overflow).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Descriptors themselves are protected control words that cannot be manipulated except for specific elements of the MCP OS (enabled by the UNSAFE block directive in NEWP).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Donald Knuth describes a similar system in Section 2.5 ‘Dynamic Storage Allocation’ of ‘Fundamental Algorithms’.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] IBM System/360 does not support virtual memory.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory isolation of jobs is optionally accomplished using protection keys, assigning storage for each job a different key, 0 for the supervisor or 1–15.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory management in OS/360 is a supervisor function.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Storage is requested using the `GETMAIN` macro and freed using the `FREEMAIN` macro, which result in a call to the supervisor (SVC) to perform the operation.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In OS/360 the details vary depending on how the system is generated, e.g., for PCP, MFT, MVT.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In OS/360 MVT, suballocation within a job's *region* or the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is based on *subpools*, areas a multiple of 2 KB in size—the size of an area protected by a protection key.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Within a region subpools are assigned either the job's storage protection or the supervisor's key, key 0.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Initially only subpool zero is created, and all user storage requests are satisfied from subpool 0, unless another is specified in the memory request.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Subpools 250–255 are created by memory requests by the supervisor on behalf of the job.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Most of these are assigned key 0, although a few get the key of the job.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Subpool numbers are also relevant in MFT, although the details are much simpler.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] MFT uses fixed *partitions* redefinable by the operator instead of dynamic regions and PCP has only a single partition.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Each subpool is mapped by a list of control blocks identifying allocated and free memory blocks within the subpool.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Memory is allocated by finding a free area of sufficient size, or by allocating additional blocks in the subpool, up to the region size of the job.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] It is possible to free all or part of an allocated memory area.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] The details for OS/VS1 are similar to those for MFT and for MVT; the details for OS/VS2 are similar to those for MVT, except that the page size is 4 KiB.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] For both OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is nonpageable.
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] In MVS the address space includes an additional pageable shared area, the *Common Storage Area* (CSA), and two additional private areas, the nonpageable *local system queue area* (LSQA) and the pageable *System Work area* (SWA).
[src:fasthttp-server/memory-management] Also, the storage keys 0–7 are all reserved for use by privileged code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Opens a new window with list of versions in this module.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] This package is not in the latest version of its module.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Opens a new window with license information.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Opens a new window with list of imports.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Opens a new window with list of known importers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] fasthttp was designed for some high performance edge cases.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] **Unless** your server/client needs to handle **thousands of small to medium requests per second** and needs a consistent low millisecond response time fasthttp might not be for you.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] **For most cases `net/http` is much better** as it's easier to use and can handle more cases.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] For most cases you won't even notice the performance difference.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Currently fasthttp is successfully used by VertaMedia in a production serving up to 200K rps from more than 1.5M concurrent keep-alive connections per physical server.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] In short, fasthttp server is up to 6 times faster than net/http.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] In short, fasthttp client is up to 4 times faster than net/http.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Unfortunately, fasthttp doesn't provide API identical to net/http.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] There is net/http -> fasthttp handler converter, but it is better to write fasthttp request handlers by hand in order to use all of the fasthttp advantages (especially high performance :) ).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] // request handler in net/http style, i.e. method bound to MyHandler struct.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] // notice that we may access MyHandler properties here - see h.foobar.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] // request handler in fasthttp style, i.e. just plain function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] // ctx.Done() is only closed when the server is shutting down.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Use this brilliant tool - race detector - for detecting and eliminating data races in your program.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] If you detected data race related to fasthttp in your program, then there is high probability you forgot calling TimeoutError before returning from RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] In performance-critical code, converting between `[]byte` and `string` using standard Go allocations can be inefficient.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Converts a `[]byte` to a `string` **without memory allocation**.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] Converts a `string` to a `[]byte` **without memory allocation**.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] The following tricks are used by fasthttp.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] So throw away nil checks for `[]byte` buffers from you code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p01] This is an **unsafe** way, the result string and `[]byte` buffer share the same bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Package fasthttp provides fast HTTP server and client API.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Easy 'Connection: Upgrade' support via RequestCtx.Hijack.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] A lot of additional useful info is exposed to request handler: - Server and client address. - Per-request logger. - Unique request id. - Request start time. - Connection start time. - Request sequence number for the current connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Client supports automatic retry on idempotent requests' failure.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Fasthttp API is designed with the ability to extend existing client and server implementations or to write custom client and server implementations from scratch.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HTTP status codes were stolen from net/http.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultConcurrency is the maximum number of concurrent connections the Server may serve by default (i.e. if Server.Concurrency isn't set).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultDNSCacheDuration is the duration for caching resolved TCP addresses by Dial* functions.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultDialTimeout is timeout used by Dial and DialDualStack for establishing TCP connections.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultLBClientTimeout is the default request timeout used by LBClient when calling LBClient.Do.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The timeout may be overridden via LBClient.Timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultMaxConnsPerHost is the maximum number of concurrent connections http client may establish per host by default (i.e. if Client.MaxConnsPerHost isn't set).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultMaxIdemponentCallAttempts is the default idempotent calls attempts count.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultMaxIdleConnDuration is the default duration before idle keep-alive connection is closed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultMaxPendingRequests is the default value for PipelineClient.MaxPendingRequests.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DefaultMaxRequestBodySize is the maximum request body size the server reads by default.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See Server.MaxRequestBodySize for details.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FSCompressedFileSuffix is the suffix FS adds to the original file names when trying to store compressed file under the new file name.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FSHandlerCacheDuration is the default expiration duration for inactive file handlers opened by FS.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Deprecated: ErrAlreadyServing is never returned from Serve.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrBodyTooLarge is returned if either request or response body exceeds the given limit.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrDialTimeout is returned when TCP dialing is timed out.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrGetOnly is returned when server expects only GET requests, but some other type of request came (Server.GetOnly option is true).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrMissingFile may be returned from FormFile when the is no uploaded file associated with the given multipart form key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoArgValue is returned when Args value with the given key is missing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoAvailableClients is returned by LBClient methods when no clients are available, for example after every client has been removed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoMultipartForm means that the request's Content-Type isn't 'multipart/form-data'.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrPipelineOverflow may be returned from PipelineClient.Do* if the requests' queue is overflowed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTLSHandshakeTimeout indicates there is a timeout from tls handshake.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTimeout is returned from timed out calls.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FSCompressedFileSuffixes is the suffixes FS adds to the original file names depending on encoding when trying to store compressed file under the new file name.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This map is read during FSHandler initialization (which runs in a sync.Once).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is not safe for concurrent modification.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Set any custom suffixes in an init() function or before the first call to FS.NewRequestHandler, and do not modify the map afterwards.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AcquireTimer returns a time.Timer from the pool and updates it to send the current time on its channel after at least timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned Timer may be returned to the pool with ReleaseTimer when no longer needed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AddMissingPort adds a port to a host if it is missing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] A literal IPv6 address in hostport must be enclosed in square brackets, as in "[::1]:80", "[::1%lo0]:80".
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendBrotliBytes appends brotlied src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendBrotliBytesLevel appends brotlied src to dst using the given compression level and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendDeflateBytes appends deflated src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendDeflateBytesLevel appends deflated src to dst using the given compression level and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendGunzipBytes appends gunzipped src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendGzipBytes appends gzipped src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendGzipBytesLevel appends gzipped src to dst using the given compression level and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendHTMLEscape appends html-escaped s to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendHTMLEscapeBytes appends html-escaped s to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendHTTPDate appends HTTP-compliant (RFC1123) representation of date to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendIPv4 appends string representation of the given ip v4 to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendInflateBytes appends inflated src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendNormalizedHeaderKey appends normalized header key (name) to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Normalized header key starts with uppercase letter.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The first letters after dashes are also uppercased.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendNormalizedHeaderKeyBytes appends normalized header key (name) to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendQuotedArg appends url-encoded src to dst and returns appended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendUint appends n to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendUnbrotliBytes appends unbrotlied src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendUnquotedArg appends url-decoded src to dst and returns appended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendUnzstdBytes appends unzstd src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendZstdBytes appends zstd src to dst and returns the resulting dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] CoarseTimeNow returns the current time truncated to the nearest second.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Deprecated: This is slower than calling time.Now() directly.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This is now time.Now().Truncate(time.Second) shortcut.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Dial dials the given TCP addr using tcp4.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This dialer is intended for custom code wrapping before passing to Client.Dial or HostClient.Dial.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] For instance, per-host counters and/or limits may be implemented by such wrappers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The addr passed to the function must contain port.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DialDualStack dials the given TCP addr using both tcp4 and tcp6.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DialDualStackTimeout dials the given TCP addr using both tcp4 and tcp6 using the given timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This dialer is intended for custom code wrapping before passing to Client.DialTimeout or HostClient.DialTimeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DialTimeout dials the given TCP addr using tcp4 using the given timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do performs the given http request and fills the given http response.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Request must contain at least non-zero RequestURI with full url (including scheme and host) or non-zero Host header + RequestURI.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoFreeConns is returned if all DefaultMaxConnsPerHost connections to the requested host are busy.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is recommended obtaining req and resp via AcquireRequest and AcquireResponse in performance-critical code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DoDeadline performs the given request and waits for response until the given deadline.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTimeout is returned if the response wasn't returned until the given deadline.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DoRedirects performs the given http request and fills the given http response, following up to maxRedirectsCount redirects.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] When the redirect count exceeds maxRedirectsCount, ErrTooManyRedirects is returned.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DoTimeout performs the given request and waits for response during the given timeout duration.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTimeout is returned if the response wasn't returned during the given timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FileLastModified returns last modified time for the file.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FlushDNSCache clears all cached DNS entries for the default dialer, forcing fresh DNS lookups on subsequent Dial* calls.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This is useful when you want to ensure fresh DNS resolution, for example after network changes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GenerateTestCertificate generates a test certificate and private key based on the given host.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Get returns the status code and body of url.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The contents of dst will be replaced by the body and returned, if the dst is too small a new slice will be allocated.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Do* for manually handling redirects.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetDeadline returns the status code and body of url.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTimeout error is returned if url contents couldn't be fetched until the given deadline.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetTimeout returns the status code and body of url.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrTimeout error is returned if url contents couldn't be fetched during the given timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ListenAndServe serves HTTP requests from the given TCP addr using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ListenAndServeTLS serves HTTPS requests from the given TCP addr using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] certFile and keyFile are paths to TLS certificate and key files.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ListenAndServeTLSEmbed serves HTTPS requests from the given TCP addr using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] certData and keyData must contain valid TLS certificate and key data.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ListenAndServeUNIX serves HTTP requests from the given UNIX addr using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The function deletes existing file at addr before starting serving.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The server sets the given file mode for the UNIX addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NewStreamReader returns a reader, which replays all the data generated by sw.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned reader may be passed to Response.SetBodyStream.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Close must be called on the returned reader after all the required data has been read.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ParseByteRange parses 'Range: bytes=...' header value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ParseHTTPDate parses HTTP-compliant (RFC1123) date.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ParseIPv4 parses ip address from ipStr into dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ParseUfloat parses unsigned float from buf.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Post sends POST request to the given url with the given POST arguments.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Empty POST body is sent if postArgs is nil.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseArgs returns the object acquired via AcquireArgs to the pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not access the released Args object, otherwise data races may occur.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseCookie returns the Cookie object acquired with AcquireCookie back to the pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not access released Cookie object, otherwise data races may occur.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseRequest returns req acquired via AcquireRequest to request pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden accessing req and/or its' members after returning it to request pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseResponse return resp acquired via AcquireResponse to response pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden accessing resp and/or its' members after returning it to response pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseTimer returns the time.Timer acquired via AcquireTimer to the pool and prevents the Timer from firing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not access the released time.Timer or read from its channel otherwise data races may occur.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseURI releases the URI acquired via AcquireURI.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The released URI mustn't be used after releasing it, otherwise data races may occur.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SaveMultipartFile saves multipart file fh under the given filename path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The path is used as-is and must be a server-trusted destination filename.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not pass the attacker-controlled fh.Filename directly without validating it and constraining it to the intended destination directory.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Serve serves incoming connections from the given listener using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Serve blocks until the given listener returns permanent error.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeConn serves HTTP requests from the given connection using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeConn returns nil if all requests from the c are successfully served.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Connection c must immediately propagate all the data passed to Write() to the client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Otherwise requests' processing may hang.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFS returns HTTP response containing compressed file contents from the given fs.FS's path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Directory contents is returned if path points to directory.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFS interprets path as a URI path internally.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Percent-encoded sequences may be decoded, and '?' or '#' may be treated as URI delimiters.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use ServeFSLiteral if you need literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFSLiteral returns HTTP response containing compressed file contents from the given fs.FS's path using literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Reserved URI characters in path such as '%', '?' and '#' are preserved instead of being interpreted during internal request URI processing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFile returns HTTP response containing compressed file contents from the given path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use ServeFileUncompressed is you don't need serving compressed file contents.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFile interprets path as a URI path internally.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use ServeFileLiteral if you need literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See also RequestCtx.SendFile, ServeFileLiteral.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WARNING: do not pass any user supplied paths to this function!
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WARNING: if path is based on user input users will be able to request any file on your filesystem!
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use fasthttp.FS with a sane Root instead.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFileBytes returns HTTP response containing compressed file contents from the given path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use ServeFileBytesUncompressed is you don't need serving compressed file contents.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See also RequestCtx.SendFileBytes, ServeFileLiteral.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFileBytesUncompressed returns HTTP response containing file contents from the given path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFileBytes may be used for saving network traffic when serving files with good compression ratio.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFileLiteral returns HTTP response containing compressed file contents from the given path using literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use ServeFileUncompressed if you don't need serving compressed file contents.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See also RequestCtx.SendFileLiteral, ServeFile.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFileUncompressed returns HTTP response containing file contents from the given path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeFile may be used for saving network traffic when serving files with good compression ratio.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeTLS serves HTTPS requests from the given net.Listener using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ServeTLSEmbed serves HTTPS requests from the given net.Listener using the given handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetBodySizePoolLimit set the max body size for bodies to be returned to the pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If the body size is larger it will be released instead of put back into the pool for reuse.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] StatusCodeIsRedirect returns true if the status code indicates a redirect.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] StatusMessage returns HTTP status message for the given status code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] VisitHeaderParams calls f for each parameter in the given header bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It stops processing when f returns false or an invalid parameter is found.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Parameter values may be quoted, in which case \ is treated as an escape character, and the value is unquoted before being passed to value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] f must not retain references to key and/or value after returning.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Copy key and/or value contents before returning if you need retaining them.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteBrotli writes brotlied p to w and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteBrotliLevel writes brotlied p to w using the given compression level and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteDeflate writes deflated p to w and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteDeflateLevel writes deflated p to w using the given compression level and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteGunzip writes ungzipped p to w and returns the number of uncompressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteGzip writes gzipped p to w and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteGzipLevel writes gzipped p to w using the given compression level and returns the number of compressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteInflate writes inflated p to w and returns the number of uncompressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteMultipartForm writes the given multipart form f with the given boundary to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteUnbrotli writes unbrotlied p to w and returns the number of uncompressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteUnzstd writes unzstd p to w and returns the number of uncompressed bytes written to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Create new instances instead and use CopyTo().
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Args instance MUST NOT be used from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AcquireArgs returns an empty Args object from the pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned Args may be returned to the pool with ReleaseArgs when no longer needed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Multiple values for the same key may be added.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AddBytesKNoValue adds only 'key' as argument without the '='.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AddNoValue adds only 'key' as argument without the '='.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] All returns an iterator over key-value pairs from args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The key and value may invalid outside the iteration loop.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Make copies if you need to use them after the loop ends.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Making modifications to the Args during the iteration loop leads to undefined behavior and can cause panics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendBytes appends query string to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Del deletes argument with the given key from query args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DelBytes deletes argument with the given key from query args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetBool returns boolean value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetUfloat returns ufloat value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetUfloatOrZero returns ufloat value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetUint returns uint value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetUintOrZero returns uint value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Has returns true if the given key exists in Args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HasBytes returns true if the given key exists in Args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Parse parses the given string containing query args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ParseBytes parses the given b containing query args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Peek returns query arg value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned value is valid until the Args is reused or released (ReleaseArgs).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not store references to the returned value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PeekBytes returns query arg value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PeekMulti returns all the arg values for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PeekMultiBytes returns all the arg values for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] QueryString returns query string for the args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetNoValue sets only 'key' as argument without the '='.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetUint sets uint value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetUintBytes sets uint value for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Sort sorts Args by key and then value using 'f' as comparison function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SortKeys sorts Args by key only using 'f' as comparison function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] For example args.SortKeys(bytes.Compare).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] String returns string representation of query args.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] f must not retain references to key and value after returning.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Make key and/or value copies if you need storing them after returning.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteTo implements io.WriterTo interface.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BalancingClient is the interface for clients, which may be passed to LBClient.Clients.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe calling Client methods from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The fields of a Client should not be changed while it is in use.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] CloseIdleConnections closes any connections which were previously connected from previous requests but are now sitting idle in a "keep-alive" state.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It does not interrupt any connections currently in use.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnsCount returns total connection count across all HostClients managed by Client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoFreeConns is returned if all Client.MaxConnsPerHost connections to the requested host are busy.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Immediately returns ErrTimeout if the deadline has already been reached.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Immediately returns ErrTimeout if timeout value is negative.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] IdleConnsCount returns total idle connection count across all HostClients managed by Client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnPoolStrategyType define strategy of connection pool enqueue/dequeue.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] A ConnState represents the state of a client connection to a server.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It's used by the optional Server.ConnState hook.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Create new object and use CopyTo instead.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Cookie instance MUST NOT be used from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AcquireCookie returns an empty Cookie object from the pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned object may be returned back to the pool with ReleaseCookie.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendBytes appends cookie representation to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned value is valid until the Cookie reused or released (ReleaseCookie).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] CookieExpireUnlimited is returned if cookie doesn't expire.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HTTPOnly returns true if the cookie is http only.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] MaxAge returns the seconds until the cookie is meant to expire or 0 if no max age.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Partitioned returns true if the cookie is partitioned.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Secure returns true if the cookie is secure.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Set expiration time to CookieExpireDelete for expiring (deleting) the cookie on the client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] By default cookie lifetime is limited by browser session.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetHTTPOnly sets cookie's httpOnly flag to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetMaxAge sets cookie expiration time based on seconds.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This takes precedence over any absolute expiry set on the cookie.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] 'max-age' is set when the maxAge is non-zero.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] That is, if maxAge = 0, the 'max-age' is unset.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If maxAge < 0, it indicates that the cookie should be deleted immediately, equivalent to 'max-age=0'.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This behavior is consistent with the Go standard library's net/http package.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetPartitioned sets the cookie's Partitioned flag to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Set value Partitioned to true will set Secure to true and Path to / also to avoid browser rejection.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetSameSite sets the cookie's SameSite flag to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Set value CookieSameSiteNoneMode will set Secure to true also to avoid browser rejection.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetSecure sets cookie's secure flag to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WriteTo writes cookie representation to w.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] CookieSameSite is an enum for the mode in which the SameSite flag should be set for the given cookie.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-httpbis-cookie-same-site-00 for details.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DialFunc must establish connection to addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] There is no need in establishing TLS (SSL) connection for https.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The client automatically converts connection to TLS if HostClient.IsTLS is set.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] TCP address passed to DialFunc always contains host and port.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DialFuncWithTimeout must establish connection to addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Unlike DialFunc, it also accepts a timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] TCP address passed to DialFuncWithTimeout always contains host and port.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrBodyStreamWritePanic is returned when panic happens during writing body stream.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrBrokenChunk is returned when server receives a broken chunked body (Transfer-Encoding: chunked).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrDialWithUpstream wraps dial error with upstream info.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNothingRead is returned when a keep-alive connection is closed, either because the remote closed it or because of a read timeout.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrSmallBuffer is returned when the provided buffer size is too small for reading request and/or response headers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReadBufferSize value from Server or clients should reduce the number of such errors.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FS represents settings for request handler serving static files from the local filesystem.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NewRequestHandler returns new request handler with the given FS settings.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned handler caches requested file handles for FS.CacheDuration.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Make sure your program has enough 'max open files' limit aka 'ulimit -n' if FS.Root folder contains many files.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not create multiple request handlers from a single FS instance - just reuse a single request handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FormValueFunc customizes how RequestCtx.FormValue resolves a value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HijackHandler must process the hijacked connection c.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If KeepHijackedConns is disabled, which is by default, the connection c is automatically closed after returning from HijackHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The connection c must not be used after returning from the handler, if KeepHijackedConns is disabled.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] When KeepHijackedConns enabled, fasthttp will not Close() the connection, you must do it when you need it.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] You must not use c in any way after calling Close().
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HostClient balances http requests among hosts listed in Addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] HostClient may be used for balancing load among multiple upstream hosts.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] While multiple addresses passed to HostClient.Addr may be used for balancing load among them, it would be better using LBClient instead, since HostClient may unevenly balance load among upstream hosts.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden copying HostClient instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe calling HostClient methods from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnsCount returns connection count of HostClient.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do performs the given http request and sets the corresponding response.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ErrNoFreeConns is returned if all HostClient.MaxConns connections to the host are busy.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] IdleConnsCount returns idle connection count of HostClient.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] LastUseTime returns time the client was last used.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PendingRequests returns the current number of requests the client is executing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This function may be used for balancing load among multiple HostClient instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetMaxConns sets up the maximum number of connections which may be established to all hosts listed in Addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] LBClient balances requests among available LBClient.Clients.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden copying LBClient instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe calling LBClient methods from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AddClient adds a new client to the balanced clients and returns the new total number of clients.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do calculates timeout using LBClient.Timeout and calls DoTimeout on the least loaded client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DoDeadline calls DoDeadline on the least loaded client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] DoTimeout calculates deadline and calls DoDeadline on the least loaded client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveClients removes clients using the provided callback.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If rc returns true, the passed client will be removed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Returns the new total number of clients.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Logger is used for logging formatted messages.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PathRewriteFunc must return new request path based on arbitrary ctx info such as ctx.Path().
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Path rewriter is used in FS for translating the current request to the local filesystem path relative to FS.Root.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned path must not contain '..' path segments due to security reasons, since such paths may refer files outside FS.Root.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned path may refer to ctx members.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NewPathPrefixStripper returns path rewriter, which removes prefixSize bytes from the path prefix.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned path rewriter may be used as FS.PathRewrite .
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NewPathSlashesStripper returns path rewriter, which strips slashesCount leading slashes from the path.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NewVHostPathRewriter returns path rewriter, which strips slashesCount leading slashes from the path and prepends the path with request's host, thus simplifying virtual hosting for static files.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PipelineClient pipelines requests over a limited set of concurrent connections to the given Addr.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This client may be used in highly loaded HTTP-based RPC systems for reducing context switches and network level overhead.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_pipelining for details.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden copying PipelineClient instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe calling PipelineClient methods from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] PendingRequests returns the current number of pending requests pipelined to the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This number may exceed MaxPendingRequests*MaxConns by up to two times, since each connection to the server may keep up to MaxPendingRequests requests in the queue before sending them to the server.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This function may be used for balancing load among multiple PipelineClient instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden copying Request instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Create new instances and use CopyTo instead.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Request instance MUST NOT be used from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AcquireRequest returns an empty Request instance from request pool.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned Request instance may be passed to ReleaseRequest when it is no longer needed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This allows Request recycling, reduces GC pressure and usually improves performance.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe re-using p after the function returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] AppendBodyString appends s to request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned value is valid until the request is released, either though ReleaseRequest or your request handler returning.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Do not store references to returned value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyGunzip returns un-gzipped body data.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method may be used if the request header contains 'Content-Encoding: gzip' for reading un-gzipped body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Body for reading gzipped request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyGunzipWithLimit returns un-gzipped body data and limits the size of uncompressed body data to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If maxBodySize <= 0, then no limit is applied.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method may be used if the response header contains 'Content-Encoding: deflate' for reading inflated request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Body for reading deflated request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyInflateWithLimit returns inflated body data and limits the size of uncompressed body data to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] You must CloseBodyStream or ReleaseRequest after you use it.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyUnbrotli returns un-brotlied body data.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method may be used if the request header contains 'Content-Encoding: br' for reading un-brotlied body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Body for reading brotlied request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyUnbrotliWithLimit returns un-brotlied body data and limits the size of uncompressed body data to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyUncompressed returns body data and if needed decompresses it from gzip, deflate, brotli or zstd.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method may be used if the response header contains 'Content-Encoding' for reading uncompressed request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Body for reading the raw request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyUncompressedWithLimit returns body data and if needed decompresses it from gzip, deflate, brotli or zstd.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The size of uncompressed data is limited to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyUnzstdWithLimit returns un-zstd body data and limits the size of uncompressed body data to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] BodyWriter returns writer for populating request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnectionClose returns true if 'Connection: close' header is set.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ContinueReadBody reads request body if request header contains 'Expect: 100-continue'.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The caller must send StatusContinue response before calling this method.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If maxBodySize > 0 and the body size exceeds maxBodySize, then ErrBodyTooLarge is returned.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ContinueReadBodyStream reads request body if request header contains 'Expect: 100-continue'.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] CopyTo copies req contents to dst except of body stream.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] GetTimeOut retrieves the timeout duration set for the Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method returns a time.Duration that determines how long the request can wait before it times out.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] In the default use case, the timeout applies to the entire request lifecycle, including both receiving the response headers and the response body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Host returns the host for the given request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] IsBodyStream returns true if body is set via SetBodyStream*.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] MayContinue returns true if the request contains 'Expect: 100-continue' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] MultipartForm returns request's multipart form.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Returns ErrNoMultipartForm if request's Content-Type isn't 'multipart/form-data'.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method is equivalent to MultipartFormWithLimit(0), i.e. no body size limit is applied during multipart parsing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveMultipartFormFiles must be called after returned multipart form is processed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] MultipartFormWithLimit returns request's multipart form and limits the read multipart body size to maxBodySize bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Read reads request (including body) from the given r.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveMultipartFormFiles or Reset must be called after reading multipart/form-data request in order to delete temporarily uploaded files.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] io.EOF is returned if r is closed before reading the first header byte.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReadBody reads request body from the given r, limiting the body size.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReadLimitBody reads request from the given r, limiting the body size.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ReleaseBody retires the request body if it is greater than "size" bytes.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This permits GC to reclaim the large buffer.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use this method only if you really understand how it works.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The majority of workloads don't need this method.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveMultipartFormFiles removes multipart/form-data temporary files associated with the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveUserValue removes the given key and the value under it in Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RemoveUserValueBytes removes the given key and the value under it in Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ResetUserValues allows to reset user values from Request Context.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is safe re-using body argument after the function returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetBodyRaw sets response body, but without copying it.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] From this point onward the body argument must not be changed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetBodyStream sets request body stream and, optionally body size.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If bodySize is >= 0, then the bodyStream must provide exactly bodySize bytes before returning io.EOF.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If bodySize < 0, then bodyStream is read until io.EOF.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] bodyStream.Close() is called after finishing reading all body data if it implements io.Closer.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Note that GET and HEAD requests cannot have body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetBodyStreamWriter registers the given sw for populating request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetConnectionClose sets 'Connection: close' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetTimeout sets timeout for the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use this method if a single URI may be reused across multiple requests.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Otherwise, you can just use SetRequestURI() and it will be parsed as new URI.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The URI is copied and can be safely modified later.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetUserValue stores the given value (arbitrary object) under the given key in Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The value stored in Request may be obtained by UserValue*.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This functionality may be useful for passing arbitrary values between functions involved in request processing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] All the values are removed from Request after returning from the top RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Additionally, Close method is called on each value implementing io.Closer before removing the value from Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SetUserValueBytes stores the given value (arbitrary object) under the given key in Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] All the values stored in Request are deleted after returning from RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Returns error message instead of request representation on error.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use Write instead of String for performance-critical code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] SwapBody swaps request body with the given body and returns the previous request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden to use the body passed to SwapBody after the function returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] UserValue returns the value stored via SetUserValue* under the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] UserValueBytes returns the value stored via SetUserValue* under the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] VisitUserValues calls visitor for each existing userValue with a key that is a string or []byte.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] visitor must not retain references to key and value after returning.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] VisitUserValuesAll calls visitor for each existing userValue.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Write doesn't flush request to w for performance reasons.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RequestConfig configure the per request deadline and body limits.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RequestCtx contains incoming request and manages outgoing response.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is forbidden copying RequestCtx instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] RequestHandler should avoid holding references to incoming RequestCtx and/or its members after the return.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If holding RequestCtx references after the return is unavoidable (for instance, ctx is passed to a separate goroutine and ctx lifetime cannot be controlled), then the RequestHandler MUST call ctx.TimeoutError() before return.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] It is unsafe modifying/reading RequestCtx instance from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The only exception is TimeoutError*, which may be called while other goroutines accessing RequestCtx.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Conn returns a reference to the underlying net.Conn.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] WARNING: Only use this method if you know what you are doing!
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Reading from or writing to the returned connection will end badly!
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This ID may be used to match distinct requests to the same incoming connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnRequestNum returns request sequence number for the current connection.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] ConnTime returns the time the server started serving the connection the current request came from.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Deadline returns the time when work done on behalf of this context should be canceled.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Deadline returns ok==false when no deadline is set.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Successive calls to Deadline return the same results.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This method always returns 0, false and is only present to make RequestCtx implement the context interface.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Done returns a channel that's closed when work done on behalf of this context should be canceled.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Done may return nil if this context can never be canceled.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Successive calls to Done return the same value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Note: Because creating a new channel for every request is just too expensive, so RequestCtx.s.done is only closed when the server is shutting down.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] EarlyHints allows the server to hint to the browser what resources a page would need so the browser can preload them while waiting for the server's full response.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Only Link headers already written to the response will be transmitted as Early Hints.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] This is a HTTP/2+ feature but all browsers will either understand it or safely ignore it.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] NOTE: Older HTTP/1.1 non-browser clients may face compatibility issues.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Err returns a non-nil error value after Done is closed, successive calls to Err return the same error.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If Done is not yet closed, Err returns nil.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] If Done is closed, Err returns a non-nil error explaining why: Canceled if the context was canceled (via server Shutdown) or DeadlineExceeded if the context's deadline passed.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Error sets response status code to the given value and sets response body to the given message.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Warning: this will reset the response headers and body already set!
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FormFile returns uploaded file associated with the given multipart form key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The file is automatically deleted after returning from RequestHandler, so either move or copy uploaded file into new place if you want retaining it.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Use SaveMultipartFile function for permanently saving uploaded file.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned file header is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] For multipart requests with untrusted input, call MultipartFormWithLimit() before FormFile.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] FormValue returns form value associated with the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The returned value is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] For multipart requests with untrusted input, either call MultipartFormWithLimit() before FormValue or provide a custom Server.FormValueFunc that uses MultipartFormWithLimit().
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Hijack registers the given handler for connection hijacking.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The handler is called after returning from RequestHandler and sending http response.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The current connection is passed to the handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The connection is automatically closed after returning from the handler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The server stops processing requests from hijacked connections.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Server limits such as Concurrency, ReadTimeout, WriteTimeout, etc. aren't applied to hijacked connections.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] The handler must not retain references to ctx members.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p02] Arbitrary 'Connection: Upgrade' protocols may be implemented with HijackHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] HijackSetNoResponse changes the behavior of hijacking a request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] If HijackSetNoResponse is called with false fasthttp will send a response to the client before calling the HijackHandler (default).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] If HijackSetNoResponse is called with true no response is send back before calling the HijackHandler supplied in the Hijack function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Hijacked returns true after Hijack is called.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned bytes are valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IfModifiedSince returns true if lastModified exceeds 'If-Modified-Since' value from the request header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The function returns true also 'If-Modified-Since' request header is missing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Init prepares ctx for passing to RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This function is intended for custom Server implementations.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Init2 prepares ctx for passing to RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] conn is used only for determining local and remote addresses.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See https://github.com/valyala/httpteleport for details.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsBodyStream returns true if response body is set via SetBodyStream*.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsConnect returns true if request method is CONNECT.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsDelete returns true if request method is DELETE.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsGet returns true if request method is GET.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsHead returns true if request method is HEAD.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsOptions returns true if request method is OPTIONS.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsPatch returns true if request method is PATCH.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsPost returns true if request method is POST.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsPut returns true if request method is PUT.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsTLS returns true if the underlying connection is tls.Conn.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] tls.Conn is an encrypted connection (aka SSL, HTTPS).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsTrace returns true if request method is TRACE.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] LastTimeoutErrorResponse returns the last timeout response set via TimeoutError* call.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] LocalAddr returns server address for the given request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] LocalIP returns the server ip the request came to.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Logger returns logger, which may be used for logging arbitrary request-specific messages inside RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Each message logged via returned logger contains request-specific information such as request id, request duration, local address, remote address, request method and request url.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It is safe re-using returned logger for logging multiple messages for the current request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned logger is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Returned value is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All uploaded temporary files are automatically deleted after returning from RequestHandler.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Either move or copy uploaded files into new place if you want retaining them.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned form is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Call this method before FormValue/FormFile if you need a limit for multipart parsing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] NotFound resets response and sets '404 Not Found' response status code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] NotModified resets response and sets '304 Not Modified' response status code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It doesn't return query arguments from RequestURI - use QueryArgs for this.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See also QueryArgs, FormValue and FormFile.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] These args are valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] QueryArgs returns query arguments from RequestURI.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It doesn't return POST'ed arguments - use PostArgs() for this.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See also PostArgs, FormValue and FormFile.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Redirect sets 'Location: uri' response header and sets the given statusCode.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All other statusCode values are replaced by StatusFound (302).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The redirect uri may be either absolute or relative to the current request uri.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Fasthttp will always send an absolute uri back to the client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RedirectBytes sets 'Location: uri' response header and sets the given statusCode.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RemoteAddr returns client address for the given request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RemoteIP returns the client ip the request came from.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ResetBody resets response body contents.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ResetUserValues allows to reset user values from Request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFile sends local file contents from the given path as response body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This is a shortcut to ServeFile(ctx, path).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFile logs all the errors via ctx.Logger.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFile interprets path as a URI path internally.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use SendFileLiteral if you need literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See also ServeFile, SendFileLiteral, FSHandler and FS.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFileBytes sends local file contents from the given path as response body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This is a shortcut to ServeFileBytes(ctx, path).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFileBytes logs all the errors via ctx.Logger.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See also ServeFileBytes, FSHandler and FS.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFileLiteral sends local file contents from the given path as response body using literal path semantics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This is a shortcut to ServeFileLiteral(ctx, path).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SendFileLiteral logs all the errors via ctx.Logger.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] See also ServeFileLiteral, SendFile, FSHandler and FS.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetBody sets response body to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetBodyStream sets response body stream and, optionally body size.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] If bodySize is >= 0, then bodySize bytes must be provided by bodyStream before returning io.EOF.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetBodyStreamWriter registers the given stream writer for populating response body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Access to RequestCtx and/or its members is forbidden from sw.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetBodyString sets response body to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetConnectionClose sets 'Connection: close' response header and closes connection after the RequestHandler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetContentType sets response Content-Type.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetContentTypeBytes sets response Content-Type.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It is safe modifying contentType buffer after function return.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetRemoteAddr sets remote address to the given value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Set nil value to restore default behaviour for using connection remote address.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SetStatusCode sets response status code.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] String returns unique string representation of the ctx.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned value may be useful for logging.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Success sets response Content-Type and body to the given values.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] SuccessString sets response Content-Type and body to the given values.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TLSConnectionState returns TLS connection state.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The function returns nil if the underlying connection isn't tls.Conn.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned state may be used for verifying TLS version, client certificates, etc.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutError sets response status code to StatusRequestTimeout and sets body to the given msg.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All response modifications after TimeoutError call are ignored.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutError MUST be called before returning from RequestHandler if there are references to ctx and/or its members in other goroutines remain.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Prefer eliminating ctx references from pending goroutines instead of using this function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutErrorWithCode sets response body to msg and response status code to statusCode.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All response modifications after TimeoutErrorWithCode call are ignored.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutErrorWithCode MUST be called before returning from RequestHandler if there are references to ctx and/or its members in other goroutines remain.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutErrorWithResponse marks the ctx as timed out and sends the given response to the client.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All ctx modifications after TimeoutErrorWithResponse call are ignored.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutErrorWithResponse MUST be called before returning from RequestHandler if there are references to ctx and/or its members in other goroutines remain.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This uri is valid until your request handler returns.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] UserAgent returns User-Agent header value from the request.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Value returns the value associated with this context for key, or nil if no value is associated with key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Successive calls to Value with the same key returns the same result.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This method is present to make RequestCtx implement the context interface.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This method is the same as calling ctx.UserValue(key).
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RequestHandler must process incoming requests.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RequestHandler must call ctx.TimeoutError() before returning if it keeps references to ctx and/or its members after the return.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Consider wrapping RequestHandler into TimeoutHandler if response time must be limited.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] CompressHandler returns RequestHandler that transparently compresses response body generated by h if the request contains 'gzip' or 'deflate' 'Accept-Encoding' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] CompressHandlerBrotliLevel returns RequestHandler that transparently compresses response body generated by h if the request contains a 'br', 'gzip' or 'deflate' 'Accept-Encoding' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] brotliLevel is the desired compression level for brotli.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] otherLevel is the desired compression level for gzip and deflate.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] CompressHandlerLevel returns RequestHandler that transparently compresses response body generated by h if the request contains a 'gzip' or 'deflate' 'Accept-Encoding' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] FSHandler returns request handler serving static files from the given root folder.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] stripSlashes indicates how many leading slashes must be stripped from requested path before searching requested file in the root folder.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned request handler automatically generates index pages for directories without index.html.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned handler caches requested file handles for FSHandlerCacheDuration.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Make sure your program has enough 'max open files' limit aka 'ulimit -n' if root folder contains many files.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Do not create multiple request handler instances for the same (root, stripSlashes) arguments - just reuse a single instance.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutHandler creates RequestHandler, which returns StatusRequestTimeout error with the given msg to the client if h didn't return during the given duration.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned handler may return StatusTooManyRequests error with the given msg to the client if there are more than Server.Concurrency concurrent handlers h are running at the moment.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] TimeoutWithCodeHandler creates RequestHandler, which returns an error with the given msg and status code to the client if h didn't return during the given duration.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RequestHeader represents HTTP request header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It is forbidden copying RequestHeader instances.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Create new instances instead and use CopyTo.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] RequestHeader instance MUST NOT be used from concurrently running goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Multiple headers with the same key may be added with this function.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use Set for setting a single header for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] If the header is set as a Trailer (forbidden trailers will not be set, see AddTrailer for more details), it will be sent after the chunked request body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AddBytesK adds the given 'key: value' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use SetBytesK for setting a single header for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AddBytesKV adds the given 'key: value' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use SetBytesKV for setting a single header for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] the Content-Type, Content-Length, Connection, Transfer-Encoding, Host and User-Agent headers can only be set once and will overwrite the previous value, while the Cookie header will not clear previous cookies.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AddBytesV adds the given 'key: value' header.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use SetBytesV for setting a single header for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AddTrailer add Trailer header value for chunked response to indicate which headers will be sent after the body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Use Set to set the trailer header later.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Trailers are only supported with chunked transfer.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Trailers allow the sender to include additional headers at the end of chunked messages.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Return ErrBadTrailer if contain any forbidden trailers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AddTrailerBytes add Trailer header value for chunked response to indicate which headers will be sent after the body.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] All returns an iterator over key-value pairs in h.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Copy key and/or value contents for each iteration if you need retaining them.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] To get the headers in order they were received use AllInOrder.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Making modifications to the RequestHeader during the iteration loop leads to undefined behavior and can cause panics.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AllInOrder returns an iterator over key-value pairs in h in the order they were received.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] The returned iterator is slightly slower than All because it has to reparse the raw headers to get the order.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] AppendBytes appends request header representation to dst and returns the extended dst.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ConnectionUpgrade returns true if 'Connection: Upgrade' header is set.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ContentEncoding returns Content-Encoding header value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ContentLength returns Content-Length header value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] It may be negative: -1 means Transfer-Encoding: chunked. -2 means Transfer-Encoding: identity.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] ContentType returns Content-Type header value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Cookie returns cookie for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] CookieBytes returns cookie for the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Cookies returns an iterator over key-value pairs request cookie in h.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DelAllCookies removes all the cookies from request headers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DelBytes deletes header with the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DelCookie removes cookie under the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DelCookieBytes removes cookie under the given key.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DisableNormalizing disables header names' normalization.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] By default all the header names are normalized by uppercasing the first letter and all the first letters following dashes, while lowercasing all the other letters.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Disable header names' normalization only if know what are you doing.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] DisableSpecialHeader disables special header processing. fasthttp will not set any special headers for you, such as Host, Content-Type, User-Agent, etc.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] If RequestHeader.Read() is called, special headers will be ignored.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This can be used to control case and order of special headers.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] EnableNormalizing enables header names' normalization.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Header names are normalized by uppercasing the first letter and all the first letters following dashes, while lowercasing all the other letters.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This is enabled by default unless disabled using DisableNormalizing().
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] EnableSpecialHeader enables special header processing. fasthttp will send Host, Content-Type, User-Agent, etc headers for you.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] This is suggested and enabled by default.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] HasAcceptEncoding returns true if the header contains the given Accept-Encoding value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] HasAcceptEncodingBytes returns true if the header contains the given Accept-Encoding value.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Header returns request header representation.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Headers that set as Trailer will not represent.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] IsHTTP11 returns true if the header is HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] Len returns the number of headers set, i.e. the number of times f is called in VisitAll.
[src:fasthttp-server/valyala-fasthttp-p03] MultipartFormBoundary returns boundary part from 'multipart/form-data; boundary=...' Content-Type.
